T rading activities on the floor of the Nigerian Stock Exchange yesterday witnessed another drop in share prices as bears sustained their grip on the local bourse following the sell- off occasioned by profit takings. The local bourse recorded 19 gainers against 26 losers to sustain bear run following decline recorded by most blue chip firms. Consequently, the All-Share Index dipped 93.23 basis points or 0.35 per cent to close at 26,790.10 index points as against 26.883.33 recorded the previous trading session, while market capitalisation of equities depreciated by N45 million from N12.975 trillion the previous day to N12.930 trillion as market sentiment remained on the negative territory. Meanwhile, a turnover of 189.8 million shares exchanged in 3,410 deals was recorded in the day’s trading. The premium sub-sector was the most active (measured by turnover volume) with 49 million shares exchanged by investors in 1,233 deals. Volume in the sub-sector was largely driven by activities in the shares of Zenith Bank Plc and FBNH Plc. Also, the banking sub-sector boosted by the activities in the shares of Fidelity Bank Plc and GTBank Plc followed with a turnover of 25.3 million shares in 435 deals. Further analysis of the day’s trading showed that in percentage terms, AG Leventis Plc and Livestocks Feeds Nigeria Plc topped the day’s gainers’ table with 10 per cent each to close at 33 kobo and 55 kobo per share respectively, while Neimeth Pharmaceuticals Plc followed with 8.96 per cent to close at 73 kobo per share. Wapic Insurance Plc added 8.57 per cent to close at 38 kobo per share. On the flip side, CHI Plc led the losers’ with a drop of 10 per cent to close at 36 kobo per share while GSK Plc shed 9.52 per cent to close at N5.70 per share. Oando Plc trailed with 9.09 per cent to close at N3.50 per share.